King Osman in 1969. Subsequent to that event and until the late 1970's, Ethiopia was involved in a series of military

confrontations with Somalia in what was described as the "Rasco problem". This confrontation with Ethiopia initiated

a security dilemma that engulfed the region and began the process of transforming Somalia into two national

conflicts.

The 1989 civil war which eliminated the existing regime gave rise to a new security dilemma which was perceived as

a threat to almost every social institution of the new state. Therefore Somalia experienced the most severe kind of

internal conflict which may have weakened the country to the extend of producing a cataclysmic social breakdown.

Increased global inter-connectivity and inter-dependence on oil and other primary commodities facilitated this process

through the strategies of direct or proxy domination in Somalia. It is not suitable at this juncture to deeply discuss how

these global factors affected the Somali political economy.

However, it is worth noting that the region witnessed 4 phases of globalization driven by the ethos of political

economy and the desirability of a liberal economic order. In its latest form, globalization evoked ethno-cultural

resource competition, prevented compromise
